insight_description: Sleep duration and quality remain low despite improvements in mood and stress survey scores.
Physical activity increased, with more steps and less sedentary time, coinciding with reduced negative affect.
Patient reports persistent fatigue and hopelessness despite some improvement in survey and session mood ratings.
Digital engagement at home decreased, with shorter and fewer phone unlocks, as mood improved.
Patient’s social interaction increased, with more outgoing calls and unique device contacts post-2021-05-09.
Patient identifies academic pressure, poor sleep, and perfectionism as triggers for distress and negative thoughts.
Despite no psychotropic medication, patient shows some benefit from mindfulness and grounding exercises.
Patient’s time in green spaces and exercise locations increased, aligning with improved mood and reduced stress.
Patient struggles with consistent use of coping strategies, often feeling overwhelmed or forgetful.
Patient’s negative self-evaluations and perfectionistic beliefs are persistent, contributing to emotional distress.
Patient’s affect and reported mood are congruent, with anxiety and tearfulness noted in session.
Patient’s daily routine shows increased variability in significant places visited and total distance traveled.
Patient’s digital engagement patterns show more frequent but shorter unlocks, possibly reflecting changes in focus.
Patient’s perceived stress and negative affect decreased, but positive affect remains low and unchanged.
Patient’s sleep onset and wake times became more consistent, but average sleep duration decreased.
Patient’s goals include regular grounding, journaling, and improving energy and focus, reflecting insight and motivation.
